<TEXT>
a federal express airplane crashed and burned 
tuesday evening in a residential area near stapleton international 
airport killing the pilot officials said 
there were no reports of injuries on the ground 
the aircraft which had been en route from aspen to denver went 
down several blocks from the southeast end of the airport the 
plane crashed into a back yard near an alley and did not hit any 
buildings 
the pilot was the only person aboard the singleengine cessna 
208 caravan said airport spokesman jack mcguire a city 
firefighter said the pilot was killed 
at the time of the crash the temperature was just below 
freezing and the weather included a combination of sleet rain and 
snow grains the national weather service said 
laura demorrow who lives near the crash site said she saw the 
plane sputtering and spiraling slowly towards the ground 
demorrow said she then saw a large fireball i saw flames and 
smoke then ran inside to call police she said 
demorrow said it sounded like the plane was stalling as it 
plunged to the ground 
police erected barricades and put up yellow rope to keep back 
hundreds of curious spectators 
federal express spokesman armand schneider said the plane had 
been flying from aspen to denver and was operated under lease by 
pm air of phoenix 
a federal express singleengine plane operated under lease by pm 
air crashed jan 17 into a mountain while flying packages from 
denver to montrose killing the pilot 
</TEXT>
