<TEXT>
the government is refusing to send its aids 
researchers into court to shed light on allegations that drug 
companies failed to move swiftly enough to prevent their blood 
products from transmitting the virus to children with hemophilia 
the centers for disease control contends aids researchers time 
is better spent in the laboratory lawyers for families of the aids 
victims say they believe both justice and science can be served by 
having the experts testify 
parents whose hemophiliac children have gotten aids from 
aidscontaminated blood are shocked that the federal government is 
refusing access to the truth about what information was given to 
people in the blood business in the early 1980s about the 
transmissibility of aids said laura anderson a miami attorney 
for families who are suing armour pharmaceutical of bradley ill 
and cutter laboratories of berkeley calif 
the government has won the first legal skirmishes most recently 
a ruling by a federal judge in atlanta that cdc experts cant be 
forced to testify in aidsrelated lawsuits 
senior us district judge charles a moye jr said he was 
concerned that compelling the experts to testify would subject the 
cdc to an onslaught of subpoenas for testimony on aids 
lawyers for families of the aids victims hope to win 
reconsideration of that ruling and a similar one in california 
the lawyers want to question aids experts bruce evatt and donald 
francis about their dealings with companies that make clotting 
products from donated blood 
according to documents filed in the case cdc researchers sent 
to at least one drug company a 1982 draft report saying 
hemophiliacs should be advised of this risk a suggestion 
missing from the cdcs subsequent official report 
the documents also say that francis advised a cdc colleague in a 
january 1983 memo that he feared it might be too late to 
prevent aids from spreading to hemophiliacs 
but he urged that the cdc recommend using only a very small pool 
of screened blood donors for manufacturing such products even 
though there will be objections by industry and blood bankers 
the atlanta ruling quashing a subpoena issued in florida means 
evatt does not have to testify but a larger issue remains when 
if ever cdc researchers should be compelled to testify in aids 
lawsuits 
the cdc has fielded about 50 requests in the last seven years 
for testimony from three top aids specialists the agency also has 
responded to more than 200 inquiries from lawyers concerned with 
such cases according to the cdc 
moye in his feb 6 order said the plaintiffs have a reasonable 
explanation for why they need evatts testimony but their 
interest in getting the deposition simply cannot compare to the 
governments interest in maximizing the use of its limited 
resources in dealing with a national health crisis 
the government contends research should take precedence 
weve taken a fairly hardnosed position on this said cdc 
legal adviser gene matthews we simply cant let our doctors and 
researchers who are spread thin as it is peel off time and go 
testifying 
a subpoena issued to francis a cdc expert in california was 
quashed by a federal magistrate there last year 
ms anderson suggested that if evatt were allowed to testify in 
her case his testimony could be videotaped and saved for use in 
other aids lawsuits 
she raised the possibility that the government wont allow the 
researchers to testify because of the possibility of embarrassing 
material coming out 
nothing was ever articulated specifically but that is sort of 
by implication what is going on ms anderson said 
cdc spokeswoman gail lloyd said the agency is not worried about 
anything embarrassing coming out in court 
already ms lloyd said we have supplied voluminous 
documents everything weve ever had has been supplied it is not 
an effort to withhold information 
francis and evatt have refused to comment on the lawsuits ms 
lloyd said 
theyre scientists and theyd just as soon do science the 
issue here is a legal issue not a scientific issue on this issue 
they just dont feel its their subject she said 
