<TEXT>
energy secretary james d watkins says a waste 
storage problem that threatened the future of the rocky flats 
nuclear weapons plant has been resolved at least until late 1991 
thats a rare piece of welcome news for rocky flats which is 
shut down for safety and management improvements the plant 16 
miles northwest of denver also is under fbi investigation for 
possible criminal violation of environmental laws 
rocky flats is the nations sole source of plutonium triggers 
for nuclear weapons 
watkins told a meeting of the national governors association on 
monday that a program of waste minimization at rocky flats will 
keep the plant within its limits of plutonium waste storage until 
august by then he said the department expects to begin operating 
a special waste compactor that will enable rocky flats to handle 
all its own waste until late 1991 no specific date was mentioned 
it was thought that rocky flats would reach its waste limit this 
spring 
rocky flats had been sending its excess waste to a weapons 
facility in idaho but when idaho gov cecil andrus blocked further 
shipments last year watkins launched an illfated effort to 
persuade seven states colorado washington idaho nevada new 
mexico tennessee and south carolina to take equal amounts of 
rocky flats waste 
watkins pleaded on national security grounds but all seven 
states turned him down 
the watkins sevenstate plan was based on the assumption that 
rocky flats would reach its waste storage limit of 1600 cubic 
yards by march or april 1990 
the department recently indicated that the crunch might be 
delayed slightly but watkins statement monday was the first word 
of a major change in circumstances 
eventually the rocky flats waste is supposed to go to a 
permanent underground storage site in the new mexico desert but 
efforts to open that facility originally scheduled for 1988 
have been plagued by delay watkins has said the new mexico dump 
could be available late this year but new delays are possible and 
the facility is unlikely to be in full operation until 1992 or 
later 
in his remarks to the governors meeting watkins said the key to 
relieving the wastestorage pressure at rocky flats was a program 
undertaken by the department and its rocky flats contractor to 
segregate and minimize the generation of plutonium wastes 
this effort has been effective in reducing the generation rate 
from 130 cubic yards per month in march 1989 to 70 cubic yards per 
month watkins said 
calls to watkins aides seeking additional details on how waste 
generation was minimized were not returned 
in a related development the department issued a report 
critical of rockwell international corp which operated rocky 
flats until the end of last year the company agreed to withdraw 
from its contract early because of a dispute with watkins over its 
approach to rocky flats environmental and safety problems 
the department said it was paying rockwell 2 million for 
running rocky flats from april through september 1989 a cut from 
the 82 million it could have earned the department said 
rockwells handling of environmental safety and health programs 
was unsatisfactory and that management was not totally 
responsive to the departments requirements 
rockwell insisted it put a high priority on environmental and 
safety issues 
</TEXT>
