funding available to rich and poor districts and after a federal 
court ruled that judicial elections in nine urban counties 
discriminated against minorities 
the state court gave lawmakers until may 1 to overhaul financing 
for the nations secondlargest school system with 33 million 
students in 1100 districts only californias school system is 
larger 
texas schools are funded with local property taxes and state 
aid funding totals more than 13 billion a year the court found 
that because of disparities in property values annual spending per 
student among texas districts ranges from 2112 to 19333 
in a 90 ruling in october the court said it would not tell the 
legislature how to correct the inequities or order it to increase 
taxes but warned a bandaid will not suffice the system itself 
must be changed 
at least six major funding proposals including one costing more 
than 1 billion are before legislators 
but state comptroller bob bullock warned lawmakers there is no 
money available for school funding reform if they do spend 
additional money they need to raise it or forever hold their 
peace he said monday 
the superintendent of san antonios edgewood school district 
the lead plaintiff in the lawsuit challenging the current school 
funding system said its time the system was made fairer 
its been too long that thousands of children in this state 
over the last 20 years have had to go through systems of education 
that did not provide them the quality of education because of a 
lack of basic equity in the school finance system james vasquez 
said 
the legislature was forced to take up election reform after a 
federal judge found that countywide elections for district judges 
in nine counties violated the voting rights act of 1965 by watering 
down black and hispanic voting strength 
at the time of us district judge lucius buntons ruling in 
november nonhispanic whites held 155 of the 172 district 
judgeships in the nine counties while blacks and hispanics make up 
about onethird of the states poulation 
bunton began dividing the counties into judicial districts in 
line and in january he ordered special elections in may for 115 
judgeships in the counties nearly onethird of the states 375 
district judges 
but a federal appeals court halted the elections saying 
lawmakers should be allowed to draw up the judicial districts 
