<TEXT>
important events in the decade the 
sandinistas have ruled nicaragua 
july 19 1979 the sandinista national liberation front enters 
managua two days after dictator anastasio somoza had fled in 
secret and begins its rule 
april 1980 violeta barrios de chamorro whose husband was 
assassinated in a killing that helped bring the sandinistas to 
power quits the governing junta claiming health problems mrs 
chamorro who succeeded her husband as publisher of the newspaper 
la prensa would soon start criticizing the sandinistas 
november first attacks by antisandinistas who became known 
as contras short for the spanish word for counterrevolutionary 
february 1981 the reagan administration announces suspension 
of aid to nicaragua and accuses the sandinista front of aiding 
leftist guerrillas in el salvador 
april 9 1984 nicaragua asks the world court to order the 
united states to stop helping the contras the reagan 
administration announces it wont accept the courts jurisdiction 
jan 10 1985 daniel ortega is inaugurated as president 
following national elections 
may 1 reagan announces a trade embargo against nicaragua 
june 27 the world court says us support of the contras 
violates the un charters ban on use of force 
aug 13 the us senate approves reagans request for a 
military aid package for the contras 
oct 5 1986 an americanmanned cargo plane is shot down over 
nicaragua surviving crew member eugene hasenfus is captured and 
implicates the cia in contrasupply operations hasenfus is 
subsequently freed 
nov 25 us attorney general edwin meese says some of the 
profits from the sale of american arms to iran were secretly 
diverted to the contras in an operation under us marine lt col 
oliver north 
aug 7 1987 five central american presidents sign a regional 
peace plan sponsored by costa rican president oscar arias he would 
subsequently receive the nobel peace prize for his efforts the 
plan called for amnesties for political prisoners democratic 
reforms an end to foreign aid for irregular forces and 
prohibiting one country from allowing its territory to be used by 
guerrillas to attack another country 
feb 3 1988 congress cuts off military aid to the contras 
but continues nonlethal aid 
march sandinistas and contras meet for the first time in 
facetoface peace talks in the nicaraguan border post of sapoa 
april 1 a formal 60day truce begins 
may 31 the sandinistas decide to extend the ceasefire on a 
monthtomonth basis the contras say they consider the truce 
indefinite fighting slackens 
july 11 us ambassador richard melton is expelled from 
nicaragua along with eight other us diplomats accused of trying 
to destabilize the sandinista government washington retaliates by 
expelling the nicaraguan ambassador carlos tunnerman and eight 
other diplomats 
september contrasandinista talks break down but thousands 
of contra guerrilla fighters are moving out of the nicaraguan 
hinterland into base camps in honduras 
jan 30 1989 ortega announces a tough austerity program to 
combat worldrecord inflation that surpassed 33600 percent in 1988 
feb 14 five central american presidents sign an accord in el 
salvador ortega promises early elections in exchange for 
dismantling the contras based in honduran jungle camps 
april 28 president bush signs a 49 million nonlethal aid 
package for the contras the package runs out feb 28 1990 
aug 7 five central american presidents meeting in tela 
honduras sign an agreement to dismantle the contras bases in 
honduras by dec 8 1989 they ask help from the united nations and 
the organization of american states the rebels are not signatories 
to that pact which says their demobilization must be voluntary 
the bush administration wants the contras to remain intact to 
guarantee that elections set for feb 25 1990 are free and fair 
aug 26 contra commander israel galeano says the rebels will 
ignore the tela accord and us advice and starts moving his troops 
back to nicaragua 
nov 1 ortega announces the lifting of the 19monthold 
ceasefire after several attacks and the infiltration of thousands 
of contra troops fighting surges briefly but returns to the low 
level it had reached earlier after the us cut off lethal aid 
nov 27 ortega refuses to deny nicaraguas role in a shipment 
of missiles found when a small plane crashes in el salvador the 
united states and el salvador accuse the sandinistas of continuing 
to help the salvadoran guerrillas who had launched their biggest 
offensive nov 11 
dec 12 ortega and four central american presidents issue a 
communique calling for the demobilization of both the salvadoran 
guerrillas and the contras 
sunday elections are held and mrs chamorros coalition 
defeats ortega 
monday ortega concedes visits mrs chamorro at her home and 
promises to promote national reconciliation transition talks begin 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

