<TEXT>
a sheriff who seized a national guard 
armory to ease jail overcrowding is relying in part on a 
300yearold statute that compels others to help him keep the peace 
or face four hours in the stocks 
it sounds funny people laugh about it now county attorney 
edward mcdonough said monday but i think people realize that the 
emergency we faced in 1990 in hampden county was something that was 
unprecedented 
the issue arose feb 16 when sheriff michael ashe seized the 
armory telling surprised guardsmen that lack of jail space posed 
an imminent danger of a breach of the peace 
on friday ashe won the right to keep inmates at the armory 
while county and state officials try to work out a compromise 
location a hearing on the matter was set march 12 
assistant attorney general lawrence fletcherhill argued the 
sheriff is a county official with no authority to take state 
property 
ashe cited a law dating from the massachusetts bay colony that 
allows a sheriff to require assistance in carrying out his duties 
with regard to criminals 
anyone refusing to help if convicted before one or more of 
his majesties justices of the peace such offender or offenders 
shall be fined to the use of the poor of the town where the 
offence shall be committed not exceeding forty shillings at the 
discretion of such justice or justices acording to the 
circumstances aggravating or lessening such offence reads the 
statute in the acts and resolves public and private of the 
province of the massachusetts bay 
those unwilling to come up with the 40 shillings could spend 48 
hours in prison or four hours in the stocks 
mcdonough said in addition to the old statute the county also 
is arguing that the sheriffs duty is to house convicted prisoners 
something his overcrowded jail wouldnt allow 
