<TEXT>
newspaper heiress iphigene ochs sulzberger 
whose powerful acquaintances included every president from coolidge 
to kennedy and whose subtle but firm influence shaped the new york 
times has died at age 97 
trustee of the family fortune and the daughter wife 
motherinlaw and mother of times publishers mrs sulzberger died 
in her sleep of respiratory failure monday at her home in stamford 
conn 
she played an important role in selecting publishers of the 
times after her father adolph s ochs acquired it in 1896 and 
she worked to expand the papers coverage of womens affairs and 
its circulation in schools 
you cannot think of iphigene ochs sulzberger without thinking 
of the new york times and it is impossible to imagine the times 
without iphigene sulzberger wrote former times editor harrison 
e salisbury in the introduction of her memoirs iphigene my 
life and the new york times 
she recalled meeting many interesting people as a child 
mark twain andrew carnegie president william howard taft adm 
richard byrd 
as an adult mrs sulzberger traveled and rubbed elbows with the 
famous she met eleanor roosevelt dined with chiang kaishek and 
sipped coffee with golda meir 
she was a white house guest of every president from calvin 
coolidge to john f kennedy and was acquainted with many heads of 
state including japanese emperor hirohito the shah of iran and 
winston churchill 
in the kingdom and the power gay talese suggested that if 
her father had permitted it mrs sulzberger might have become a 
journalist a crusading sort urging reform 
but she disagreed saying a single course at the columbia school 
of journalism represented the first and only time i aspired to 
become a journalist 
people often think that i must have reached some profound 
conclusions about life and that what i have to say is to be taken 
very seriously she said in her memoirs 
ochs appointed her to the times board of directors in her 20s 
after he died in 1935 she was one of three trustees along with 
her husband and then her son of the ochs estate which owns the 
controlling interest in the paper 
to perpetuate her fathers dream mrs sulzbergers four 
children and her grandchildren entered into agreements that will 
continue family control of the times indefinitely 
newspapers were the birthright of iphigene bertha ochs the 
granddaughter of rabbi isaac m wise founder of judaisms reform 
movement 
on sept 19 1892 the night she was born in cincinnati her 
father then publisher of the chattanooga times was in new york 
fighting to get smaller papers accepted in the associated press 
in 1904 young iphigene helped lay the cornerstone for the 
times building at times square 
sometime later her father dismayed by iphigenes fascination 
with vulgar comics in competitor papers started the times 
first and last comic strip the roosevelt bears 
young iphigene judged their adventures wordy and 
uninteresting and the bears became extinct after a year and a 
half 
salisbury said her impish nature emerged in childhood and she 
remained irrepressible as an adult 
at age 9 she signed a thankyou note to president theodore 
roosevelt love and kisses at 12 she was expelled for 
impertinence from dr sachs school for girls at 16 she 
enjoyed the rides at coney island with guglielmo marconi inventor 
of the wireless 
an economics major she graduated from barnard college an a 
student despite having dyslexia a learning disability unknown at 
the time 
she became engaged to arthur hays sulzberger at a 
romanticlooking park in spartanburg sc which turned out to 
be the grounds of the local lunatic asylum according to her 
memoirs they were married in 1917 completing their washington 
honeymoon with a white house meeting with president woodrow wilson 
her husband retired in 1961 their soninlaw orvil e dryfoos 
held the publishers post until his death in 1963 their son 
arthur ochs sulzberger known as punch has been publisher 
since then their grandson arthur ochs sulzberger jr is deputy 
publisher 
mrs sulzbergers other children are marian sulzberger heiskell 
the widow of orvil dryfoos and wife of andrew heiskell retired 
chairman of time inc ruth sulzberger holmberg publisher of the 
chattanooga times and dr judith p sulzberger a new york doctor 
she had 13 grandchildren and 24 greatgrandchildren 
funeral services were scheduled for wednesday at temple emanuel 
</TEXT>
