<TEXT>
orders to us factories for durable goods 
plunged 105 percent in january the biggest decline since orders 
first were tracked 32 years ago the government reported today a 
drop in aircraft orders led the way 
the commerce department said orders for durable goods 
bigticket items expected to last more than three years totaled a 
seasonally adjusted 1182 billion last month after increasing a 
revised 14 percent in december that figure originally was 
reported to be up 25 percent 
the steepest decline until januarys record was a 92 percent 
fall in february 1982 
most of the decline was in transportation equipment the 
department said aircraft and parts which had been unusually 
high in the last several months accounted for nearly half of the 
january decline in transportation although motor vehicles and 
parts and shipbuilding and tanks were both down sharply 
aircraft orders represented onethird of the overall decline 
auto production also fell in january as tens of thousands of auto 
workers were laid off to help the industry shrink swollen 
inventories the department considers car orders and production to 
be the same 
the drop helped pull overall transportation orders down 276 
percent to 279 billion 
much of the economys recent weakness has been concentrated in 
durable goods as the federal reserve sought for more than a year to 
drive down inflation by keeping a tight rein on credit the result 
has been higher interest rates which adversely affect durable 
goods orders because they often are financed by loans 
excluding the transportation industry orders fell 34 percent 
the closely watched nondefense capital goods sector often a 
barometer of business investment plans fell 137 percent 
reversing decembers 142 percent gain the sector also posted 
gains in october and november 
electrical machinery orders dropped 176 percent to 188 
billion after rising 56 percent in december and 73 percent in 
november virtually all of the decrease was in communications 
equipment the commerce department said 
orders for nonelectrical machinery including computers and a 
wide variety of industrial equipment rose 26 percent to 223 
billion after falling 39 percent in december 
primary metals orders were up 15 percent to 111 billion 
following a 28 percent decline in december 
new orders for defense capital goods a highly volatile sector 
plummeted 36 percent to 63 billion for the lowest onemonth 
volume of orders since january 1987 defense orders had slipped 
129 percent in december after rising 177 percent in november 
excluding defense orders would have been off 34 percent 
shipments of durable goods in january dropped 37 percent to 
1177 billion after falling 08 percent a month earlier 
