<TEXT>
people held against their will at state mental 
hospitals without receiving legally required hearings may sue 
officials in federal court for monetary damages the supreme court 
ruled by a 54 vote today 
the justices reversing lower court rulings said a florida man 
may sue in federal court over being held in a florida state 
hospital for five months without a hearing that state law requires 
within 48 hours 
writing for the court justice harry a blackmun said people 
raising such claims are not limited to suing for damages in state 
courts 
darrell burch was found wandering along a florida highway dec 
7 1981 he was taken to a tallahassee community health services 
center where he was held for three days 
during that time burch was hallucinating he believed he was in 
heaven 
after his stay at the center burch was transferred to the 
florida state hospital where he remained until may 7 1982 his 
lawsuit alleges that he was heavily medicated and disoriented when 
arriving at the state hospital 
despite a state law that entitled him to a hearing within 48 
hours of his admission to challenge his detention and treatment 
burch did not receive a hearing 
his federal lawsuit alleged that 11 officials and employees of 
the florida state hospital acted with willful wanton and 
reckless disregard of and indifference to his dueprocess rights 
the suit invoked a muchused civil rights law 
a federal judge threw out the suit ruling that burch was barred 
from filing it because he could win adequate relief in state court 
a threejudge panel of the 11th us circuit court of appeals 
upheld the dismissal but the entire appeals court voted 85 to 
reinstate the suit 
todays decision upheld the 11th circuit courts ruling and 
burchs lawsuit can now proceed 
blackmun wrote that previous high court decisions limiting 
access to federal courts if adequate state court remedies exist do 
not apply to burchs case because the deprivation of burchs 
liberty was not unpredictable 
under floridas statutory scheme only a person competent to 
give informed consent may be admitted as a voluntary patient 
blackmun said there is however no specified way of 
determining before a patient is asked to sign admission forms 
whether he is competent 
therefore blackmun said it is hardly unforeseeable that a 
person requesting treatment for mental illness might be incapable 
of informed consent and that state officials with the power to 
admit patients might take their apparent willingness to be admitted 
at face value 
blackmun was joined by justices william j brennan byron r 
white thurgood marshall and john paul stevens 
chief justice william h rehnquist and justices sandra day 
oconnor antonin scalia and anthony m kennedy dissented 
the case is zinermon vs burch 871965 
