<TEXT>
authorities today defended police checkpoints 
as an effective weapon against drunken driving but an attorney for 
a group of michigan motorists told the supreme court the stops 
violate privacy and do not work 
we think they are very effective said thomas l casey 
assistant state solicitor general in michigan they do result in 
arrests of drunk drivers they do have a deterrent effect they do 
have an educational effect 
mark granzotto a detroit lawyer representing the motorists 
argued however as a means of acting against drunken driving 
sobriety roadblocks are worthless 
they dont work granzotto said when challenged by chief 
justice william rehnquist to explain why they were ineffective 
justice byron white asked granzotto why if the roadbocks are 
ineffective many states have adopted them 
they are a very visible means of showing that something is 
being done the lawyer replied 
casey argued that the intrusion into peoples privacy has been 
kept to a minimum under the michigan procedure 
he said people have to be willing to be a little bit 
inconvenienced because of the seriousness of the drunkendriving 
problem 
granzotto said he did not disagree that the problem is serious 
however he said we have an intrusion that may be minimal in 
some respects but it is an intrusion that does not accomplish 
anything 
the courts decision is expected by july 
lower courts have split on the issue some have upheld the use 
of checkpoints others like the michigan courts have ruled that 
such police tactics violate privacy rights 
president bush called on state and local governments in december 
to step up the fight against drunken driving 
its as crippling as crack as random gang violence and its 
killing more kids than both combined he said 
the president noted that state and local governments are 
receiving federal aid to operate sobriety checkpoints 
michigan state police first used sobriety checkpoints which 
they modeled after a program used in maryland in 1986 
at a checkpoint site police directed all traffic headed in one 
direction to a roadside area where officers checked motorists for 
signs of intoxication 
if there was no immediate evidence of intoxication the motorist 
was given a traffic safety brochure and allowed to drive away the 
average delay was about a halfminute 
if some signs of intoxication were detected a driver was 
directed to another area for further questioning and perhaps a 
breath test 
at one such checkpoint michigan state police troopers checked 
126 vehicles in less than an hour and detained two drivers for 
sobriety field tests one driver was arrested on drunken driving 
charges 
seven michigan residents sued the state police soon after the 
checkpoint program began their lawsuit alleged that the 
checkpoints violated the fourth amendments ban on unreasonable 
police searches and arrests 
state courts struck down the practice citing the potential 
for an unreasonable subjective intrusion on individual liberty 
interests 
michigans appeal is being supported in friend of the court 
briefs by 27 states and groups including the national governors 
association the national league of cities mothers against drunk 
driving and the alliance of american insurers 
the supreme court in 1979 barred police from randomly stopping 
vehicles to check registration papers in that delaware case 
officers had total discretion over which vehicles were stopped 
but the 1979 decision did not rule out spot checks in which an 
officers discretion was not so unconstrained questioning of all 
oncoming traffic at roadblocktype stops is one possible 
alternative the decision said 
at issue in a separate case from pennsylvania also being heard 
today was whether motorists must be given socalled miranda 
warnings before police videotape their taking sobriety field tests 
the court will decide by july whether police violated a 
motorists rights when they videotaped his answers to questions 
about his height weight and eye color before telling him he could 
remain silent and was entitled to have a lawyer present 
the cases are michigan state police vs sitz 881897 and 
pennsylvania vs muniz 89213 
