<TEXT>
a kgb agent who worked for the british for 13 
years says he escaped his country by pretending to go on his daily 
jog in moscow and catching a train to the finnish border 
oleg gordievsky who described his flight to the west in a 
bbctv interview broadcast monday also said some of the british 
spy scandals that have made headlines were baseless and damaging 
it was a waste of time waste of resources waste of paper 
all those articles were published the former spy said there 
was great damage and the public morale and the trust to the 
intelligence security services in western countries was impaired 
it was a pity it was totally unnecessary 
gordievsky said sir roger hollis who headed britains mi5 
counterespionage service from 1956 to 1965 was not a soviet agent 
writer chapman pincher and former mi5 officer peter wright 
whose book spycatcher the british government failed to suppress 
after lengthy court battles have alleged the late hollis was 
almost certainly a soviet spy 
pincher responding to gordievskys remarks said the kgb 
restricted information about highlevel double agents and that 
gordievsky would have been too junior to have known 
gordievsky said he was in a position to know if the kgb had 
recruited highlevel agents like hollis 
it was inconceivable really not to know if there had been such 
an important agent of kgb if a person like him had been kgb agent 
the people would have gossiped gordievsky said there would 
have been some indication in the files there were no signs of it 
at all 
gordievsky began to work for the british in copenhagen in the 
early 1970s after becoming disillusioned with the soviets 
particularly after the 1968 invasion of czechoslovakia 
he was transferred to london where he became one of the top kgb 
agents in britain he first learned that the soviets were 
suspicious of his activities in 1979 when a senior agent confronted 
him and six other kgb members about intelligence leaks he said 
and of course i knew that i was the source of leaks 
gordievsky said it demanded from me a tremendous selfcontrol 
and concentration not to reveal myself by body language by a 
gesture 
he said he was called to moscow in 1985 under false pretenses 
and then questioned about his activities he revealed nothing 
despite being drugged during interrogations but knew he had to 
escape 
i was very worried two or three days later when i started to 
recollect the whole content of the interrogation i realized that i 
was under strong suspicion and my life was in great danger 
he would not speak of the contacts that enabled him to escape 
but described how he stuffed his sweatsuit with identification 
papers and money then set off on his daily jog past kgb 
surveillance 
gordievsky ran to the moscowleningrad rail station where he got 
a train west to the finnish border and defected he would not say 
how he achieved the crossing 
he said his only regret was that he had to leave his wife 
leila and two daughters 
i didnt betray the country i didnt betray the people of the 
soviet union i think i betrayed the regime and the soviet 
communist system which was illegitimate wrong and in many periods 
of the soviet history even criminal he said 
gordievsky wearing a tweed jacket and smoking a pipe smiled 
easily and spoke quietly in slightly accented but very good english 
i feel myself quite well integrated into british society in 
many aspects i am like a normal british citizen with similar habits 
and customs for example the greatest sunday pleasure is to spend 
the morning reading sunday newspapers sometimes in bed 
and even i never could have expected it from me myself but 
i have developed an interest for gardening he said 
