the foreign ministry has admitted it has found 
copies of the secret protocol of the 1939 sovietnazi pact that 
allotted the three independent baltic nations and part of poland to 
the soviet union 
vestnik a new soviet magazine published by the foreign 
ministry showed photographs in its premier edition that came out 
on monday of a typewritten russianlanguage copy of the secret 
additional protocol 
the soviet union has maintained it could not find any evidence 
of the protocols in its archives and still says it does not have 
the originals 
last summer soviet publications printed germanlanguage copies 
of the protocols kept in the archives of the west german foreign 
ministry 
also last summer soviet leader mikhail s gorbachev supported 
the creation of a commission to investigate claims there was such a 
protocol he said at the time that no documents had been found to 
confirm the existence of the protocol 
the protocol was signed by stalins foreign minister vyacheslav 
molotov and hitlers top diplomat joachim von ribbentrop on aug 
23 1939 a week before the outbreak of world war ii 
the document placed the independent countries of estonia latvia 
and lithuania and parts of eastern poland in the soviet sphere of 
influence and was the basis of stalins decision later to annex 
that territory to the soviet union 
the baltic republics succeeded in winning soviet government 
recognition of the existence of the protocols last year 
the magazine also published a statement by one of molotovs 
aides confirming the original had been handed over to another aide 
another confirmation of the existence of the originals 
vestnik a joint venture between the soviet union and austria 
is edited in moscow and printed in vienna and costs 75 a year for 
the monthly publication 
