<TEXT>
the houses chief tax writer said tuesday he 
sees absolutely no way to increase tax collections next year by 
the 139 billion president bush is proposing 
the remarks by ways and means committee chairman dan 
rostenkowski dill further dimmed the prospects that congress 
and the bush administration will quickly forge a deficitreduction 
plan for fiscal 1991 which begins oct 1 
meanwhile rostenkowskis panel voted to urge the budget 
committee to take the surpluses of the social security trust fund 
out of budget deficit calculations a move that would greatly 
worsen the federal deficit problem on paper 
as part of his plan to find 375 billion in deficit reductions 
next year bush last month proposed increasing tax receipts by 
139 billion the administration estimates that cutting the 
capital gains tax would increase revenue by 49 billion with the 
rest coming from greater internal revenue service efficiency and 
increases in several minor taxes 
democratic leaders of the house and senate budget committees 
have said they oppose the ingredients of bushs plan especially 
the rate cut on capital gains taxes which they say would mainly 
benefit the wealthy they have said they might try to produce a 
budget of their own containing the same amount of new revenue 
139 billion but with a different mix 
but rostenkowski told his panel such a tack would prove 
unworkable 
i see absolutely no way we can raise 14 billion and thats 
the direction the budget committee is taking us he said 
the illinois democrat said that if his committee is told to find 
14 billion in new taxes were just not that good a magician 
unless we become very serious about reaching out for revenues that 
are certainly going to be ducks 
the word ducks was a reference to white house budget 
director richard darmans statement last year that bushs pledge of 
no new taxes applies to any levies the public would perceive as 
taxes he used the expression that if something walks and talks 
like a duck its a duck 
bush has repeatedly promised to veto increases in such taxes 
congress democratic leaders have said that therefore they will 
propose no tax increases that will provoke a veto and leave their 
party as the sole advocate of higher taxes 
the ways and means panel voted tuesday by voice against 
rostenkowski to ask that social security trust fund surpluses be 
removed from deficit calculations 
supporters of the proposal sponsored by rep byron dorgan 
dnd said the surpluses make the federal deficit appear smaller 
the public thus feels less urgency to address the problem they 
said 
it was the first congressional vote of the year on the issue 
which has been a focus of attention on capitol hill since sen 
daniel moynihan dny proposed cutting the social security 
payroll tax 
