<TEXT>
a small party backed by west german 
chancellor helmut kohl said tuesday the east german elections 
should be postponed because voting rules were not available in time 
to permit fair competition 
the german social union told the supreme court its chances and 
those of other small parties were hurt because national newspapers 
did not publish procedures for the march 18 ballot the first free 
election in east germanys 40year history 
parliament approved the regulations a week ago in the form of a 
lengthy voting law which was printed and made available at 
bookstores friday it set monday as the deadline for parties to 
notify the national election committee if they planned to run 
candidates 
representatives of the german social union known as the dsu by 
its german initials got a copy of the law from the election 
committee friday and were able to register before the deadline 
its complaint to the court said newly formed parties had too 
little chance to prepare candidate lists for the 400 parliament 
seats which must be given to the committee by wednesday and asked 
that the vote be delayed at least until early may 
elections originally were scheduled for may 6 but the german 
social union and other parties pressed the communistled interim 
government to move the date up partly from fear the economy would 
collapse before may 
some larger parties including the communists have political 
networks with offices telephones vehicles and other advantages 
not available to new groups that have sprung up since the 
prodemocracy movement began last fall 
even so the clear leader is the social democratic party 
founded less than five months ago and supported by the sister party 
that is west germanys main opposition 
polls of east german voters predict the social democrats will 
get at least 50 percent of the vote march 18 
kohls christian democratic union supports the german social 
union east german christian democratic union and democratic 
awakening which are joined in a conservative alliance 
thousands of east germans cheered kohl at a rally last week in 
erfurt but it was no match for the emotional welcome given former 
chancellor willy brandt at a weekend rally of social democrats in 
leipzig 
putting off the election would give the smaller parties a fairer 
chance said joachim novak deputy chairman of the german social 
union 
we have argued from the beginning that it is unfair for the 
new parties to have to compete against organized forces so soon 
he said 
as a minimum the regulations should have been published in 
the newspapers failure to distribute the procedural information 
broadly is clearly a violation of the constitution 
east german newspapers remain technically under government 
control although they have undergone great changes since the 
hardline leadership of erich honecker was ousted in october none 
published the text of the election law 
many government offices and enterprises have virtually halted 
operations until the elections allow plans for economic rescue and 
german reunification to proceed 
west germany has offered to make its deutschmark the official 
currency of both germanys but only after a democratically elected 
government is in power and laws are rewritten to foster conversion 
to a freemarket economy 
