<TEXT>
just over half the respondents in a new survey 
say they feel the bush administrations lawenforcement approach to 
the war on illegal drugs will reduce the countrys drug problem 
at the same time slightly more than onethird say they favor 
legalization for less serious drugs and an increase in drug 
treatment and education programs 
national drug control policy director william j bennett who 
has called legalization advocacy stupid and morally atrocious 
dismissed the survey saying some progress has been made in the war 
on drugs 
now that were starting to see some encouraging signs why put 
up the white flag he rhetorically asked reporters at the white 
house 
the telephone poll of 1401 adult americans was done jan 
24feb 4 by targeting systems inc of arlington va for the drug 
policy foundation which says it advocates treating drug abuse as a 
health problem not a criminal justice issue the survey has a 
margin of error of 3 percentage points 
richard j dennis of chicago chairman of the foundations 
advisory board paid for the survey 
among the polls findings 
55 percent of the respondents said they believe the 
administrations primarily law enforcement approach to the war on 
drugs including more prison sentences for casual drug use using 
the military to fight drug trafficking and more money for prisons 
is likely to reduce the drug problem 
36 percent favor legalization of less serious drugs along with 
an increase in drug treatment and education aid 
asked if it was more important to take any step necessary 
in order to stop drug use than to protect civil liberties 71 
percent chose taking any step necessary 
fewer than 2 percent said they might try cocaine if it were 
legalized but 60 percent say they think cocaine use would go up if 
it were no longer a crime ten percent said cocaine use would 
decrease if it were legalized and 27 percent said it would stay the 
same 
96 percent said they might try marijuana if it were legalized 
while 50 percent said marijuana use would increase if it were not a 
crime twelve percent said it would decrease and 37 percent said it 
would stay the same 
given the choice between providing treatment and counseling for 
drug users or punishing them with fines and imprisonment 68 
percent favored treatment and 21 percent favored punishment 
61 percent said all drug use is immoral and should be illegal 
while 35 percent disagreed with that view 
as for medical uses of some prohibited drugs 76 percent said 
doctors should be allowed to prescribe heroin as a painkiller for 
terminally ill cancer patients while 69 percent said physicians 
should be allowed to prescribe marijuana as a treatment for 
glaucoma 
