administration for example was that ortega could never be counted 
on to hold a free and fair election 
the perception of ortega as an antidemocrat guided every policy 
decision concerning nicaragua that the administration took the 
notion that ortega would hold a fair election and agree to turn 
over power if he lost was laughable a tall tale belonging on the 
fiction shelf 
several years ago one official who had the audacity to suggest 
that ortega was a moderate in the sandinista political context was 
looked on almost as a subversive by administration hardliners he 
was banished to appen after a sandinista victory giving the alternative 
possibility short shrift 
their views of course were fed by the pollsters who were 
predicting a sandinista victory in excess of 15 percentage points 
it is now obvious that a significant number of nicaraguans gave the 
safe answer to the pollsters that they were prosandinista 
in the privacy of the voting booth they abandoned ortega 
one of the few who was not taken in by the pollsters was the 
chief us diplomat in managua jack leonard who foresaw the 
chamorro victory weeks ago 
the pollsters were no less off base than former assistant 
secretary of state elliott abrams who in an april 1987 speech 
predicted disaster for central america if military aid to the 
contras was cut off 
under abrams scenario an aid suspension would enable the 
sandinistas to devote their attention to subverting other central 
american countries leading to the eventual destruction of the 
fledgling democracies in the region 
to abandon the contras is to follow a recipe for certain 
disaster in the region within two years he said 
abrams grim scenario has not panned out military aid was 
indeed cut off by the congress the date was two years ago this 
week and instead of disaster befalling nicaraguas neighbors it 
befell the sandinistas themselves 
</TEXT>
