at least 47 people were killed and 200 
wounded by bombs factional battles or police during voting tuesday 
for legislatures in eight indian states news agencies reported 
press trust of india said 45 people were killed in bihar an 
eastern state that is among indias poorest and two in the western 
state of gujarat 
it said an election officer died of a heart attack in 
mountainous himachal pradesh state 
bihar is notorious for organized gangs that operate during 
elections one of the victims there was an independent candidate 
shot and killed by unidentified gunmen 
three of the 45 victims in bihar were killed by police who 
opened fire near patna the state capital to stop stuffing of 
ballot boxes united news of india reported it said the others 
were killed by bombs or in fights between members of rival 
political parties 
about 150 million voters cast ballots for 1610 members of the 
eight legislatures all of which have been controlled by the 
congress party of former prime minister rajiv gandhi 
the elections were seen as a test of the congress partys waning 
popularity and the rising voter appeal of the rightwing bharatia 
janata or indian peoples party 
more than 45000 members of federal security forces were 
deployed for the elections 18000 of them in bihar thirteen 
people were killed during election campaigning in the eight states 
including 11 in bihar 
about 70 percent of the 213 million registered voters turned out 
in arunachal pradesh bihar gujarat himachal pradesh madhya 
pradesh maharashtra orissa and rajasthan states results are not 
expected until wednesday 
elections also were held in pondicherry a federally 
administered territory in the south and in five national 
parliamentary constituencies and 17 state legislative districts 
where byelections were due or elections had been canceled because 
candidates died 
in novembers national elections indians voted the congress 
party out of power replacing it with the national front coalition 
of prime minister vp singh 
the alliance of singhs janata dal or peoples party and three 
minor factions is supported by the the bharatia janata and 
communists 
gandhis congress party entered candidates for all but 30 of the 
state legislative seats the janata dal and bharatia janata were in 
about 1000 contests each 
more than half the 21200 candidates were independents 
the hindustan times of new delhi said the elections were being 
conducted under what is regarded as the tightestever security 
arrangements in view of the increasing incidence of poll violence 
and booth capturing 
booth capturing covers a variety of activity from stuffing 
of ballot boxes to intimidation that sometimes ends in murder 
