<TEXT>
john c lawn will retire as head of the drug 
enforcement administration next month after five tumultuous years 
when drugs and related violence commanded the attention of the 
american people 
lawn whose retirement was announced tuesday took over the 
agency in 1985 just as mexican authorities were discovering the 
bodies of slain dea agent enrique kiki camarena and his mexican 
pilot alfredo zavala avelar 
lawns role in pressuring mexican officials to pursue those 
behind the kidnaptortureslaying of the two was portrayed last 
month in a television miniseries called drug wars the camarena 
story 
in an interview in december lawn gave no hint that he might be 
retiring this year as head of the lead federal agency for drug law 
enforcement 
when asked how long he would like to keep his job lawn said 
until i become tired of it 
he acknowledged that the job was frustrating and 
challenging and added some point in time will come that ill 
have to turn over the reins but i dont know when thatll be 
one reason behind the decision to retire after 27 years of 
government service is that he will turn 55 in a few months said 
dea spokesman frank shults 
while lawn as a presidential appointee is exempt from the 
mandatory retirement age of 55 imposed on other federal law 
enforcement officers he would not be able to maintain his 
position as a law enforcement officer just an administrator 
shults said its extremely important to him that he is a 
special agent thats his motivation 
theres no suggestion that hes giving up the war on drugs 
shults said hes very torn it was an extremely difficult 
decision for him to make 
in a letter to president bush announcing his intention to retire 
march 23 lawn said my service as administrator of dea over the 
past five years has been most rewarding and most satisfying the 
ratification of the united nations convention the national drug 
control strategy and the cartagena summit have established the 
foundations upon which we can project with confidence our ultimate 
success in this battle 
lawn also thanked bush for your personal involvement in 
honoring those dea special agents who have paid the ultimate price 
in this battle saying that action combined with support for the 
agents families have special significance for the men and women 
of the drug enforcement administration and for me 
in the december interview lawn said the toughest part of his 
job was the loss of personnel such as camarena he also expressed 
disappointment with the size of the drug war budget contrasting 
the 95 billion budget for 1990 to the excess of 30 billion a 
year the united states spent for the vietnam war 
to have fewer agents than there are musicians in the united 
states army or to have fewer agents than there are new york city 
transit police you get a sense of too few people being asked to 
face a herculean challenge lawn said 
just as lawn is leaving the bush administration has requested a 
budget of 106 billion for the war on drugs in 1991 a sum that 
would boost deas share from 6169 million this year to 7913 
million next year enough to add several hundred new agents to the 
current complement of 3191 when lawn took over the job in 1985 
the dea budget was 3538 million 
lawn who was born in brooklyn ny plans to return to new 
york city for a job in the private sector said shults who did not 
give details of lawns new job 
jack lawn has provided extraordinary leadership to the drug 
enforcement administration during an extremely challenging time 
attorney general dick thornburgh said in a statement he has been 
a catalyst for leadership in the international law enforcement 
community helping to unite the drugfighting efforts of many 
countries his contributions to the international war on drugs 
will be missed 
lawn a former marine corps officer joined the fbi in 1967 and 
served in savannah ga monterey calif kansas city mo san 
antonio texas and at fbi headquarters before he became acting 
deputy administrator of dea in 1982 
president reagan nominated lawn to the top dea job in 1985 to 
replace francis m mullen who had retired 
