katell roc a regional mineral water 
bottled and sold in western france went out of business tuesday 
after reports that its water was contaminated with hydrocarbons 
water quality problems for the small bottler which employed 35 
people at its spring and plant at lizio in britanny arose about 
the same time traces of benzene were found in perrier sparkling 
water 
the plant closure came as the governments consumer watchdog 
agency the national institute of consumption called for labels on 
all mineral water to bear the date it was bottled 
the perrier experience showed the negative effects and 
legitimate suspicion that can follow in case of an accident when 
there is no clear bottling date the agency said 
katell roc president pierre mignot suspended work at the plant 
feb 8 a day after perrier issued its global recall there were 
reports that contaminated katell roc water had ended up in a baby 
bottle 
katell roc recalled 1 million bottles and ran tests on samples 
to check purity and restore consumer confidence mignot said but 
traces of hydrocarbons were found in the bottles spring and pipes 
chlorine also was found in the pipes 
the widespread contamination meant the company could not return 
to production said mignot without specifying the nature of the 
hydrocarbons or how much money the company had lost 
our financial situation is untenable we are only a small 
company mignot said the katell roc brand no longer exists 
the discovery by a us laboratory that forced source perrier sa 
to recall 160 million bottles of its popular brand from 120 
countries on feb 7 has led to greater scrutiny of bottled water 
last week the vittel mineral water concern recalled 1 million 
to 2 million bottles of its domestic hepar brand after reports that 
some had been contaminated with the hydrocarbon alkane 
the company already had quietly withdrawn the contaminated water 
from the shelves but issued a public general recall of new bottles 
to end confusion among consumers executives said 
the consumer agency said it had tested 27 mineral waters since 
the perrier recall two weeks ago and said only perrier showed 
traces of benzene or other chemicals above european standards it 
said the results should restore public confidence in spring water 
and bottled mineral water 
the withdrawal has been voluntary in france with the decision 
left to distributors and shops whether to pull the pearshaped 
green bottles off shelves 
