the scandal brought down the administration of former prime 
minister noboru takeshita and led to the resignation of his 
successor sousuke uno who stepped down to take responsibility for 
the july election outcome 
but kaifu led the liberal democrats to an unexpectedly wide 
majority in the feb 18 lower house election giving him and his 
party renewed confidence in their leadership 
kaifu lacks a significant power base within the party but 
nevertheless insisted on a clean cabinet he stubbornly 
resisted former finance minister michio watanabes backing of koko 
sato an exagriculture minister and member of watanabes 
intraparty faction 
sato had been given a suspended sentence in a 1970s scandal in 
which lockheed aircraft corp bribed politicians to influence sales 
of its aircraft in japan 
watanabe relented however when cabinet negotiations became 
stalemated kaifu also rebuffed attempts from another party faction 
to include a recruitlinked member in the cabinet 
but kaifus insistence on a recruitfree cabinet could cost him 
heavily said takashi inoguchi a political scientist at tokyo 
university 
kaifus dilemma is that to gain public approval he has to 
assert himself visavis other major bosses inoguchi told kyodo 
news service but unless kaifu incorporates recruittainted 
politicians major bosses may not cooperate with him 
kaifu from a small party faction depends on support from the 
big party bosses takeshita exforeign minister shintaro abe and 
exfinance minister kiichi miyazawa all linked to recruit and 
heads of the three largest factions 
other lawmakers appointed to the cabinet included former 
agriculture minister kabun muto as minister of international trade 
and industry justice minister shin hasegawa labor minister 
shunpei tsukahara construction minister tamisuke watanuki and 
defense agency director general yozo ishikawa 
