<TEXT>
the nations pension insurance agency urged 
the supreme court tuesday to leave intact its ability to prevent 
companies from abandoning responsbility for worker benefits 
the high court heard oral arguments in a case seen by the bush 
administration as an important test of the authority of the pension 
benefit guaranty corporation a government corporation that insures 
the pensions of 30 million americans 
at issue is whether ltv steel co will succeed in dumping 
billions of dollars in pension costs onto pbgc 
the court must decide whether pbgc acted properly in ordering 
ltv steel a subsidiary of dallasbased ltv corp to reassume 
responsibility for three pension plans 
the vastly underfunded plans were taken over by the pension 
agency after ltv corp sought protection from creditors under 
chapter 11 bankruptcy laws in 1986 
but pbgc attorney carol connor flowe told the court tuesday that 
the agency sought to turn the plans back to ltv because the 
companys financial conditions improved and because the firm 
entered into a followon arrangement with workers 
under the arrangement ltv and the united steelworkers of 
america agreed that the firm would make up the difference of any 
benefits lost to employees because of the pension terminations the 
idea was that the pbgc would pay basic pension benefits to the 
workers while the ailing firm would kick in supplemental benefits 
400 per month in many cases not covered by the government 
plan 
but flowe said such a followon arrangement represented an 
abuse of the pension insurance program 
under questioning by justice sandra day oconnor about pbgcs 
authority flowe said ltvs followon deal and its improved 
economic state by august 1987 each were independent grounds for 
turning the pension plans back to the company 
congress flowe said provided pbgc with broad powers to restore 
terminated plans in 1974 by passing the employee retirement income 
security act or erisa 
what congress said was that pbgc should make this 
determination flowe said 
at issue she said was pbgcs right to discourage unwarranted 
terminations of pension plans by firms eager to gain a 
competitive advantage 
but ltv attorney lewis b kaden argued that the agencys action 
was at odds with the 1974 federal law which he said was designed 
to protect pensioners rights 
he said pbgc wrongly determined that ltv could afford the 
previously terminated plans 
in order to return all these plans you have to answer the 
fundamental question which is can the company afford it 
kaden said 
if the plans are turned back at least one them would likely 
have to be terminated a second time because it has no assets he 
said 
that kind of pingpong effect could not have been contemplated 
by the drafters of erisa he said 
a federal judge threw out the pbgcs order for restoration of 
the plans and the 2nd us circuit court of appeals upheld that 
ruling last may 12 
the pbgc already has a more than 1 billion deficit and says the 
ltv claims would more than double that figure 
labor secretary elizabeth dole says the case will have 
farreaching ramifications for the retirement security of workers 
and pensioners across the country 
the court is expected to rule by july 
the case is pbgc vs ltv 89390 
</TEXT>
