the senate on tuesday refused to cut off 
debate on a resolution designating an armenian genocide leaving 
the future of the measure up in the air 
it was the second time in two weeks that senate minority leader 
bob dole rkan has tried and failed to end a filibuster 
against the resolution the vote was 5148 against dole who needed 
60 votes to invoke cloture 
dole has pledged to keep fighting for the measure saying he 
might ask for another vote to end the filibuster or introduce the 
resolution in a different form 
the measure which designates april 24 as national day of 
remembrance of the 75th anniversary of the armenian genocide of 
19151923 has created a firestorm in turkey which strenously 
objects to the use of the word genocide 
dole who became familiar with armenian issues when a doctor of 
armenian descent treated him for injuries he received in world war 
ii fought strenously for the measure 
he said americans of armenian heritage deserved to be recognized 
for their suffering and called the resolution a human rights 
issue on tuesday dole met with a group of elderly people from new 
jersey and pennsylvania who lived through the events of the ottoman 
empire in the early 20th century 
the alleged genocide occurred before the birth of the current 
republic of turkey the armenians claim 15 million were killed 
because of their race 
but turkish officials say there was no genocide they say some 
600000 people including muslims and christians were killed in 
the turbulent times because of civil strife and marauding bands 
sen robert byrd dwva led a filibuster against the dole 
resolution he began talking against the measure last week arguing 
the resolution would poison relations between the united states and 
turkey a nato ally 
the turkish government has threatened retaliatory action against 
the united states if the resolution passes if the resolution 
passes the senate it would go to the house and eventually to 
president bush if both chambers approved it 
the bush administration opposed the dole resolution but dole 
said tuesday that white house officials would not object to 
softening the language and making it a socalled concurrent 
resolution bush would not have to sign such a measure 
