the national transportation safety board 
rejected an appeal tuesday from a los angeles lawyer to reopen its 
investigation into the kentucky church bus crash that killed 24 
children and three adults 
the fourmember board voted unanimously to reject a petition on 
behalf of lawrence and janey fair who lost their 14yearold 
daughter shannon in the may 14 1988 crash board members said 
lawyer john p coale failed to raise any new evidence related to 
the crash 
the board completing its investigation last march said the 
crash clearly was caused by a drunken pickup truck driver but also 
cited characteristics of the 11yearold former school bus as 
contributing to its severity 
the pickup driver larry mahoney was sentenced friday to 16 
years in prison after being convicted of 27 counts each of 
seconddegree manslaughter and firstdegree wonton endangerment and 
one count of drunken driving 
mahoneys truck going the wrong way on interstate 71 near 
carrollton ky slammed headon into the bus which was quickly 
engulfed in flames 
the board in rejecting coales petition noted that it had 
already recommended improved standards for protecting school bus 
fuel systems 
coale contended that the bus involved in the accident contained 
significant construction and design defects that may have 
contributed to the puncturing of its fuel tank and the entry of 
smoke and fire into the passenger area 
the board in its investigation recommended that older school 
buses used by churches and other groups be retired since they do 
not meet stricter safety standards that have applied to school 
buses since 1977 
