<TEXT>
an appellate court considering a lawsuit 
against a doctor who refused to treat an aids patient heard 
arguments tuesday centering on whether a private physicians office 
is a public accommodation subject to antidiscrimination laws 
the state division of human rights has accused orthopedic 
surgeon daniel elstein of syracuse of violating state 
antidiscrimination laws by refusing to treat ronald derby four 
years ago 
derby who had been elsteins patient since 1982 died of 
acquired immune deficiency syndrome last summer at age 36 he had 
claimed that elstein refused to treat a back ailment in 1986 after 
derby revealed he had aids 
the doctor claims he did not treat derby because he was not 
specially trained to treat aids and instead referred him to an 
aids clinic 
a similar case against a dentist was argued before an appeals 
court in new york city two weeks ago 
the central issue in the elstein lawsuit is whether a doctors 
office is a place of public accommodation as defined in new 
york states antidiscrimination laws 
the division of human rights backed by a coalition of state 
civil rights and aids rights groups argued that a doctors office 
meets the definition the law was intended to prohibit 
discrimination by doctors and other medical professionals in 
providing medical services said albert j kostelny an attorney 
for the human rights agency 
elstein did not restrict his practice in any way except to 
exclude those afflicted with aids kostelny said 
elstein whose case is supported by the state medical and dental 
societies argued that a doctors office is private and not subject 
to the agencys rulings a state judge agreed with elstein in 1988 
ruling that a physicians office is distinctly private 
the division of human rights appealed to the courts appellate 
division the agency argued that allowing private physicians to 
refuse treatment to aids patients would force them to seek care at 
public hospitals and clinics and force a collapse of the entire 
public health system in new york state under the sheer weight of 
the numbers of actual and suspected aids patients 
in new york which has a high concentration of the nations aids 
cases it is especially urgent that physicians not be allowed to 
discriminate on the basis of whether a patient has the disease 
kostelny argued in his brief 
but elsteins attorney catherine a gale said the case is not 
about whether doctors should treat aids patients 
elstein referred derby to the aids clinic rather than treating 
him based on medical considerations not because he didnt want 
to treat an aids patient she said 
deciding whether to treat a patient or to refer him to a 
specialist is clearly a matter of professional judgment gales 
brief said a lay body such as the state human rights division 
is not competent to address issues involving the practice of 
medicine 
in a friendofthecourt brief the state medical society said 
that while no patient should be refused treatment simply because of 
aids an agency of nonmedical professionals should not intrude on 
physicians autonomy 
gale said a more appropriate forum for such cases would be the 
state health departments office of professional medical conduct 
whose board includes medical professionals 
a complaint about elsteins refusal to treat derby was lodged 
with the medical conduct board but an investigation found 
insufficient evidence to take action or hold a formal hearing a 
spokeswoman for the office said 
the appeals court is not expected to issue a decision for at 
least six weeks gale said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

