<TEXT>
the pentagon on tuesday assailed a decision by 
house democrats to force the military to accept more than 850 
million in budget cuts that could mean the dismissal of tens of 
thousands of men and women by october 
it would be devastating to our forces its a really terrible 
idea complained pentagon spokesman pete williams 
the subject of the dispute is the pentagons request to congress 
to avoid massive layoffs by shifting 852 million to personnel from 
other accounts mostly for procurement of aircraft vehicles and 
weapons the cuts are required under the grammrudman budget 
cutting law 
house armed services committee chairman les aspin dwis wrote 
pentagon officials that he has reluctantly decided not to bring 
their request before his committee his decision which has the 
backing of house speaker thomas s foley dwash dooms the 
request since his committee is one of four that must approve it 
president bush had the option of exempting military personnel 
from the grammrudman law but he didnt aspin argued in a memo to 
committee members that while bushs decision is painful for the 
military the administration must realize that accepting the 
grammrudman cuts meant accepting their results 
conceding that his decision will cause real pain aspin 
wrote his colleagues if we dont stand firm now this 
administration will have us playing chicken with the budget every 
year distorting the deficit reduction process and relying on us to 
save it from its more irresponsible excesses 
if congress does not allow the pentagon to switch the money 
williams said rough estimates show that 44100 to 68200 military 
personnel would have to be fired by oct 1 between 32500 and 
32600 people would be frozen in their current jobs 57000 to 
67000 promotions would be delayed and 59900 to 115900 fewer men 
and women could be brought into the armed forces 
currently there are about 21 million men and women in uniform 
some members of congress argue the bush administration brought 
the problem on itself in last years budget agreement the 
administration got congress to agree to four months worth of 
automatic spending cuts under the grammrudman budget law 
however williams argued defense secretary dick cheney was 
directed by congress in the defense spending bill to request 
approval of the transfer 
williams quoted the bill as saying the request should be made 
to prevent a return to the 1970s phenomenon of the hollow army 
in which many units were substantially undermanned 
williams said the pentagon has been preparing dramatic 
decreases in force size but to be executed judiciously over a 
period of years 
you dont simply reach in and yank out a certain number of 
people in the force you have to look at the question of 
recruiting people that graduate from military academies 
promotions people who rotate from one position to another and the 
total size of the force and you have to do that very carefully and 
deliberately williams said 
this would have an absolutely devastating effect on our men 
and women in uniform if congress denies us the ability to 
reprogram money in the 90 budget in order to soften the blow of 
the spending cuts on our military personnel williams said 
aspin issued a statement saying the administration last year 
let personnel take cuts and that made the cuts on favored weapon 
systems smaller putting weapons before people was their decision 
and now theyre stuck with it 
