<TEXT>
rural communities suffering from lost jobs and 
declining population would have more flexibility to spend federal 
development money if a bill approved tuesday by the house 
agriculture committee becomes law 
money now placed in three funds sewer and water improvements 
business development or community facilities could be shifted 
from one use to another depending on the needs of the community 
each community would name a local committee to decide priorities 
reps glenn english dokla and tom coleman rmo who 
drafted the measure said it solves the problem of differing needs 
in declining rural economies around the country 
english said his subcommittee on rural development interviewed 
250 witnesses in washington and local areas before designing the 
legislation 
each had a different idea on what rural development meant 
said english one thing they all agreed on was that they wanted 
more money 
but because of the pressures the deficit puts on the budget 
there is no more money said english 
he said his bill allows regional committees to decide how to use 
the money that is available instead of relying on washington to 
make the decisions 
some are going to need more water and sewer work said 
english we say fine take the money from some other area and 
shift it to your needs 
the agriculture department would still have authority over the 
funds but priorities would be set locally 
rep charles rose dnc opposed the plan saying it put too 
much strain on the sewer and water fund which is the largest of 
the three with about 400 million this year compared to 100 
million for business development and 100 million for community 
facilities 
rep h martin lancaster dnc said communities might divert 
money to business develpment and let infrastructure suffer 
im afraid water and sewer will get resources only when there 
is an emergency said lancaster 
rose offered an amendment to the bill that would have removed 
water and sewer money from the pool of funds but english fought 
off his effort by proposing an amendment that limited the amount of 
money that could be shifted 
coleman said the bill is compatible with a report recently 
released by president bushs economic policy council working group 
on rural development 
he said those findings showed 
rural america needs help 
federal rural development programs must look beyond traditional 
farm programs 
rural development is essentially an economic issue 
economic stress hurting most rural communities is primarily 
nonagricultural 
rapid change in rural american demands tighter coordination of 
federal rural development programs 
local community leadership is at the heart of any successful 
rural development program 
english and colemans bill creates a rural development 
administration within the agriculture department to direct federal 
policies 
it also sets up an information center to be a clearinghouse for 
ideas that have proven successful in some rural communities 
this will help small town america become more competitive in 
todays global economy said coleman 
last summer the senate passed a rural development bill 
sponsored by sen patrick leahy dvt chairman of the senate 
agriculture committee that differs greatly from the house measure 
it has three basic provisions 
a 300 million revolving fund that would provide seed money for 
businesses 
satellite educational and health communication systems 
improved drinking water 
</TEXT>
