<TEXT>
a federal judge on tuesday refused to 
overturn the conviction of a 24yearold hacker who unleashed a 
worm program that paralyzed thousands of computers nationwide 
in 1988 
us district judge howard munson set sentencing for robert 
morris for may 4 in syracuse 
the suspended cornell university student faces up to five years 
in prison and a 250000 fine for unleashing a computer worm that 
immobilized an estimated 6000 computers across the country 
including ones at the national aeronautics and space 
administration military installations and major universities 
the arnold md man was the first person brought to trial under 
a section of a 1986 federal computer fraud and abuse law that makes 
it a felony to break into and use a federal computer network 
his lawyer thomas guidoboni said prosecutors did not prove 
morris had actually broken the law because he technically had 
access to the cornell university computer system where the virus 
was introduced 
but the judge said morris had entered computer files he was not 
supposed to us justice department lawyer mark rasch said morris 
had described his own conduct to investigators as a breakin 
the federal judge also rejected guidobonis argument that a new 
trial be ordered because a remark by justice department lawyer 
ellen meltzer about terrorism inflamed a community sensitive 
about terrorist acts 
meltzer had told the jurors during closing arguments in the case 
that they shouldnt thank morris for prompting an increase in 
computer security just as they wouldnt thank a terrorist for 
increased airport security 
this remark was particularly insensitive in syracuse because 35 
students in a syracuse university program were killed in december 
1988 when a terrorist bomb exploded on pan am flight 103 over 
lockerbie scotland the lawyer said 
but munson said the objectionable remark was an isolated 
event in an otherwise fair trial 
morris dressed in a gray suit sat quietly as the lawyers 
argued guidoboni said it has not been decided whether he will 
appeal the verdict 
during his trial witnesses testified that the worm did not 
permanently harm the computers or computer files but in some cases 
people were unable to use their computers for several days while 
the virus was hunted down and removed 
morris testified during his trial that he had made a programming 
error that caused the worm to go berserk and cripple the internet 
system on nov 2 1988 he said he did not intend to cause 
permanent damage to computer files only to infiltrate the 
networks security 
prosecutors contended that morris may not have intended harm 
but that he deliberately broke into internet and took deliberate 
steps to make his worm difficult to detect and eradicate 
