<DOCNO> AP900227-0206 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
if you harbor any doubts that life is a 
business stop and consider the recordkeeping work that the 
government requires of the 100 millionplus people who pay us 
income taxes 
the assignment starts with but is by no means limited to 
filing a tax return on time each year the rules also require you 
to be ready to support that return with documents on just about any 
question that the internal revenue service might raise 
so even people who farm out their tax affairs to paid advisers 
often find themselves with boxes or file drawers full of records 
that threaten to overflow 
at this time of year especially the issue tends to arise how 
long must one hang onto all those canceled checks from some year in 
the administration of president ford is there any simple system to 
use in determining when to throw old tax records away 
the short answers to those questions in order are it 
depends and probably not but cumbersome as the process of 
tax recordkeeping may be experts on the subject say it need not 
be totally unmanageable 
the basic rule of thumb is that all documents related to tax 
matters should be kept for a minimum of three years after the date 
on which a return is filed or due whichever comes later 
that is the standard period in which the government has a legal 
right to take action on your return 
the limitation period stretches to six years in cases where it 
is determined that a taxpayer failed to report income amounting to 
25 percent or more of the total listed on any years return 
as a matter of course we recommend that you keep all your 
canceled checks for six years says the accounting firm of ernst 
amp young in this years edition of its arthur young tax guide 
before you toss your pile of 1979 records in the trash bin 
furthermore advisers suggest that you give some thought to a few 
other eventualities 
for one thing in cases of fraud or failure to file any return 
the statute of limitations may extend indefinitely 
additionally you might give the documents a quick review before 
pitching them to see if they contain any information of lasting 
relevance 
that applies in particular to anything that might affect the 
cost basis of property you own that you might one day sell at a 
capital gain subject to tax 
suppose you installed new kitchen cabinets in your home in 1979 
proof of expenses for such lasting improvements can lower the tax 
you might owe when the time comes to sell the house 
or to put it the other way around an absence of such proof 
might well mean that you have to pay far more in taxes when you 
sell than the law would otherwise have required 
for a variety of purposes tax specialists generally agree that 
you should keep copies of your yearly tax returns indefinitely 
kmpg peat warwick accountants suggest another reason to curb 
any instinct you feel to get rid of tax records as soon as possible 
occasionally new tax legislation that benefits the individual 
is made effective retroactively this may provide the opportunity 
to file an amended tax return and collect a refund but only if 
you have the appropriate records 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

