<TEXT>
theres no couch in psychiatrist lia dobrayas 
office at the salvation army adult rehabilitation center just a 
couple of straightbacked chairs a metal desk and some file 
cabinets 
but the doctor who spent the first 27 years of her career in the 
soviet union calls the office her palace and to the downtrodden 
who come through the door to try to beat drug or alcohol addiction 
its a trip toward sobriety 
the happiest moment really of my life in america was when 
the salvation army hired me said dobraya a therapist at the 
126bed center the past year 
dobraya is one of 11 clinical staffers at the salvation armys 
largest drug and alcohol rehabilitation center in the country 
this was something she wanted to do she came to us said 
the centers administrator maj robert bodine one of her first 
thoughts when she came to the united states was to somehow be 
involved with the salvation army in terms of reflecting her own 
values in wanting to be involved with people and to help them 
the christianoriented charitable agency wraps the spiritual 
approach into the educational and clinical aspects of treating at 
no charge alcoholics and drug addicts 
dr dobraya had a great deal of experience in treating 
alcoholism and drug addiction in the soviet union said dr 
