<DOCNO> AP900227-0235 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the boeing co did not violate a federal 
conflictofinterest law when the defense contractor paid 485000 
in severance to five employees who left to take government jobs 
the supreme court ruled today 
by a 90 vote the justices overturned a ruling supported by 
the bush administration that the money must be turned over to the 
government 
justice john paul stevens writing for the court said the 
payments give rise to a possible appearance of impropriety 
but he said the conflictofinterest law also permits 
corporations to encourage qualified employees to make their 
special skills available to the government 
as long as the employee has not begun working for the 
government the law does not prohibit the payment stevens said 
he said any ambiguity must be resolved in favor of government 
contractors and employees receiving severance pay until congress 
plainly states that we have misconstrued the law 
the law makes it a crime for any private party to pay and a 
government employee to receive supplemental compensation for the 
employees government service the statute is one of many federal 
laws aimed at prevent bribery graft and conflicts of interest 
todays decision reversed a 1988 ruling by the 4th us circuit 
court of appeals that said boeing paid the money illegally to the 
employees to compensate them for taking lowerpaying jobs in the 
reagan administration 
the bush administration urged the supreme court to uphold the 
appeals court ruling 
justice department lawyers said the payments were classic 
violations of federal law because they were calculated to make up 
the difference between the employees salaries at boeing and their 
government pay 
in seattle boeing spokesman paul binder said the company was 
pleased by the decision and feels vindicated after almost eight 
years of legal questions surrounding the payments 
the payments compensated employees for accrued sick leave 
unused benefits and stock options and were always completely open 
and aboveboard and disclosed to the government he said 
its not only a victory for boeing but a victory for the 
government because it means that qualified people will not feel 
impeded in taking their industrydeveloped experience and expertise 
in to government positions binder added 
boeing stopped making such payments following the initial legal 
challenge the company needs to study the high courts decision 
before deciding whether to resume them binder said 
the five former employees are 
thomas k jones who received 132000 from boeing before 
becoming deputy undersecretary of defense for strategic and theater 
nuclear forces in 1981 herbert a reynolds 80000 deputy 
director of space and intelligence policy in 1981 melvin r 
paisley 183000 assistant secretary of the navy for research 
engineering and systems in 1981 
also lawrence h crandon 40000 a computer scientist for the 
nato air command and control systems in 1982 and harold kitson 
50000 deputy assistant secretary of the navy for command 
communications and control intelligence in 1982 
the former employees said in their appeal to the supreme court 
that they were not responsible for pentagon contracting or 
procurement and that they had exemplary records with the government 
they said there was no question of divided loyalties for any of 
them because each received an irrevocable severance payment 
before entering government service 
paisley became a defense consultant after leaving the pentagon 
in 1987 his name arose in a justice department investigation of 
trafficking in confidential bid information on government 
contracts but he was never charged criminally 
his lawyers in response to court documents denied that paisley 
violated the law 
the cases are crandon vs us 88931 and boeing vs us 
88938 
</TEXT>
