<TEXT>
actions by japans financial regulators and stock 
exchange officials to calm troubled markets in recent days appeared 
sometimes contradictory and in many cases ineffective traders and 
analysts said tuesday 
stock prices plunged on a day when officials asked stock market 
participants to limit program trading some have blamed for 
worsening recent price declines 
the government also has intervened in the currency markets to 
support the value of the japanese yen and in the bond market to 
push interest rates lower which tends to depress the yen 
regulators are trying to settle a tokyo stock exchange whose key 
index has plunged by 14 percent this year partly due to worries 
about rising inflation and higher interest rates 
on monday the exchange asked securities houses to limit 
arbitrage dealings whe the stock market is declining arbitrage 
programs involving rapid trading of huge numbers of shares to 
profit from price discrepancies between stocks and stockindex 
futures has been blamed for worsening price declines 
but with arbitragers inactive monday the stock market took its 
biggest plunge since the october 1987 crash on tuesday despite 
some 201 million worth of arbitrageselling and a temporary 
decline the benchmark nikkei stock average of 225 selected issues 
closed 57608 points higher 
it is rather difficult to evaluate the market reaction from 
just one day of trading stock exchange spokesman hironobu 
takahashi said tuesday but i believe our member firms understood 
our request and tried to cooperate 
new yorkbased salomon brothers one of the leading arbitrage 
firms in tokyo stated tuesday that the action taken yesterday 
may do more harm than good it does not address the fundamental 
factors driving the market 
all the fingerpointing at arbitrage is wrong said kevin 
parker director of futures and options at morgan stanley another 
big american arbitrage player less than 5 percent of daily 
volume has been arbitrageselling it cant really explain the 
correction in the market 
parker said market fundamentals such as rising interest rates 
and inflation accounted for the downturn 
these problems have been the target of divergent actions by the 
finance ministry and the bank of japan 
the finance ministry primarily is interested with protecting 
government bond prices thereby curbing interest rate rises and 
promoting economic expansion said jason james a strategic analyst 
with james capel pacific however the central bank is concerned 
with battling inflation and supporting the value of the yen which 
are achieved by raising interest rates james said 
the ministry also reportedly was concerned that higher interest 
rates would cause japanese investments to flow back from overseas 
particularly from the united states 
the finance ministry has intervened three times in the last 
week its first bond market intervention since 1987 purchasing 
604 million worth of 10year government bonds on monday in an 
attempt to raise their prices and reduce their yields 
mondays intervention reduced yields on the benchmark 10year 
government bond to 6875 percent from a high of 7015 percent 
however the ministry stayed out of the market tuesday and the 
yield climbed to 691 percent 
bond dealer shinji kokubun of sanwa bank suggested the ministry 
may have to spend a lot more to get the job done 
the finance ministrys buying operation does not have an 
immediate effect as far as i know it works gradually he said 
the ministrys efforts may aid the stock and bond markets but 
they seemed to diverge from the central banks moves to depress 
interest rates 
bank of japan governor yasushi mieno on monday refused to rule 
out a widely anticipated increase in the banks official discount 
rate to battle inflation 
we dont change monetary policy only because stock prices 
or the yen move rapidly we have to consider carefully what the 
interest rate increases will bring how prices will change in the 
future he said 
the central bank regards the discount rate the interest it 
charges commercial banks for loans as a key weapon against 
inflation it raised the rate three times in 1989 bringing it from 
25 percent to the present 425 percent but inflation continues to 
threaten due to rising oil and labor prices 
the central banks currency operations its other weapon against 
inflation also have been hindered by market forces 
the bank reportedly spent 2 billion tuesday to bolster the yen 
but the dollar rose 038 yen and closed at 14903 yen its highest 
level since last june 15 the weaker yen makes imported items such 
as oil more expensive in japan 
</TEXT>
