<TEXT>
the us trade deficit narrowed to 1132 
billion last year the smallest since 1984 despite the highest 
level of foreign oil imports in 10 years the government reported 
tuesday 
the commerce department said the deficit shrank by 11 percent 
from an imbalance of 1272 billion in 1988 reflecting continued 
growth in american exports especially manufactured goods and 
agricultural products 
the 134 percent increase in exports which rose to a record 
3619 billion more than offset a 64 percent gain in imports 
which also hit an alltime high of 4751 billion 
tuesdays report on merchandise trade as calculated on a balance 
of payments basis confirmed trends already noted in the 
departments monthly merchandise trade reports which showed a 
deficit for all of 1989 of 1086 billion 
the new figure is higher because it excludes military sales by 
the us government and makes other minor adjustments in the 
monthly figures 
for the fourth quarter the trade deficit posted an increase of 
09 percent to 288 billion following a deficit of 286 billion 
in the third quarter 
it marked the second consecutive quarter in which the trade 
deficit failed to show improvement and private economists 
expressed fears that the deficit could begin widening again in 1990 
a higher trade deficit would spell trouble for the bush 
administration which is counting on further export growth to prop 
up the us economy 
one of the most ominous signs for the future is the surge in oil 
imports which shot up 28 percent last year to 503 billion the 
price per barrel rose to 1708 up from 1434 in 1988 while the 
number of barrels imported daily increased to 806 million the 
highest level since 1979 a year in which americans sat in gasoline 
lines because of shortages 
nonpetroleum imports were also up last year rising 4 percent 
to 4249 billion car imports from japan declined for the third 
consecutive year reflecting the fact that more japanese models are 
being manufactured in plants located in the united states 
nonfarm exports were up 14 percent to 3204 billion last year 
reflecting increases in consumer goods and manufactured capital 
goods especially commercial aircraft 
us farm sales increased 9 percent to 414 billion the volume 
of shipments of corn wheat and soybeans jumped 24 percent to 
record levels with onehalf of that increase coming in higher 
sales to the soviet union the government reported 
in the fourth quarter exports climbed 16 percent to 921 
billion but this was offset by a 14 percent increase in imports 
which rose to 1209 billion both imports and exports were at 
record levels in the final three months of the year the sixth 
consecutive quarter they have set new highs 
but paul getman an economist with regional financial 
associates said that us export growth for manufactured goods is 
likely to slow in coming months reflecting higher interest rates 
in such countries as japan and west germany higher interest rates 
dampen demand by raising the cost of borrowing for both businesses 
and consumers 
the 1132 billion trade deficit for 1989 was the smallest 
imbalance since a 1125 billion deficit in 1984 the first year 
that the trade deficit climbed above the 100 billion mark 
</TEXT>
