<TEXT>
dogged by an unclear corporate image greyhound 
corp announced tuesday it is changing its name to greyhound dial 
corp to distinguish itself from the troubled nationwide greyhound 
busline that it formerly owned 
this name change will help clarify who we are and what we 
do greyhound dial chairman john w teets told a news conference 
in new york 
the company a diversified manufacturing and financial services 
concern based in phoenix sold the bus line in 1987 to dallas 
investor fred currey who later merged it with the trailways bus 
system and renamed the operation greyhound lines inc its drivers 
have threatened to strike on friday in a wage dispute 
teets said the new name was chosen because of the importance of 
the companys dial corp subsidiary a consumer products maker with 
brands ranging from dial soap to purex detergents to lunch bucket 
microwave meals 
he said the word greyhound was retained as part of the name 
because it is an integral part of the name of several other 
subsidiaries such as greyhound financial corp and greyhound food 
management 
for the corporation to abandon the greyhound name would be a 
genuine blow to these companies he said 
the companys board of directors approved the name change on 
feb 15 
clive chajet an expert on corporate name changes said the 
company is attempting to redefine the word greyhound to be more 
than a bus service 
greyhound as a bus service is a well engrained symbol he 
said 
name changes usually are an expression of a companys longterm 
strategy rather than a reaction to a specific event said chajet 
the chairman of lippincott amp margulies inc a corporate image 
consulting firm 
asked why the company had waited until now to make the name 
change teets said it had been studying such a move for a few 
years but the threatened strike at greyhound lines was kind of 
the last grain of sand in the hourglass 
he didnt rule out eliminating the word greyhound from the 
company name in the future 
as a reflection of the confusion caused by the greyhound name 
teets said the companys switchboard had been deluged with calls 
from the press seeking details about the possible bus strike the 
company also was concerned that institutional investors might think 
it was involved in the strike 
were not involved in any way at all teets said he 
declined to comment on the bus lines labor trouble 
greyhound was primarily known for its bus service until 1987 
when it sold the line to currey for 270 million its main 
businesses now are consumer products financial services and 
catering 
a strike by drivers at greyhound lines would disrupt the 
countrys only nationwide bus system serving 9500 communities 
</TEXT>
