<TEXT>
japanese automakers praised for quickly 
developing new cars are so fast in bringing out some new products 
that they blur distinctions between two models of the same car 
outgoing ford motor co chairman donald petersen said tuesday 
petersen steps down thursday as leader of the worlds 
secondlargest automaker at a time that ford and other us 
companies retrench operations as their market shrinks and as they 
struggle to curb costs 
one costsaving area for us automakers is to cut the time for 
developing a new car and bring it to dealers the big three have 
been taking leads from their associations with japanese companies 
to reduce that time 
petersen whose company is in ventures with mazda motor corp 
and nissan motor co ltd of japan said theres risk in being too 
fast 
the japanese are changing their rate that isnt necessarily 
doing them a lot of good i dont think im abnormal in my 
inability to identify one car from another said petersen who 
has worked in the industry for nearly 41 years 
one company considered to have an exceptionally quick product 
cycle time is honda motor co ltd yet its 1990 accord which honda 
advertises as an entirely new vehicle has been criticized for not 
being distinctive enough from earlier models 
petersen became ford president in 1980 at the nadir of the 
companys fiscal troubles and took over as chairman and chief 
executive officer on feb 1 1985 
in 1980 ford lost 15 billion petersen led ford out of its 
slump aided by the marketing of such popular vehicles as the 
taurus and the company posted an industryrecord 53 billion 
profit in 1988 
petersen is departing as the us auto industry struggles to 
hold down costs in a diminishing market that is threatened more 
than ever by cars made by japanese companies overseas and in the 
united states 
petersen said he wanted to be remembered at ford for his work in 
developing a nostar system 
i wanted people to have a sense of teamwork he said since 
petersen has been chairman and with influence from mazda ford has 
begun adapting a japanese teamoriented manufacturing method 
ford owns 25 percent of mazda and gets its probe cars from 
mazdas plant in flat rock mich later this year ford will make 
the mazda navajo sportutility vehicles at its plant in louisville 
ky 
but when asked outside of ford which automaker he most admired 
petersen said toyota motor corp 
they have a very complex product line he said they are a 
very big company and sell in very high volume there are others 
companies but they are more limited in their product line 
im extraordinarily impressed with the west german bmw 
petersen said and the other company that impresses me is 
frances peugeot i think their cars are beautifully designed 
taking over for petersen is vice chairman harold poling who 
will be chairman for three years speculation is that executive 
vice president alan gilmour who becomes president of the ford 
automotive group on thursday will succeed poling 
during the next 18 months general motors corp chairman roger 
b smith and chrysler corp chairman lee iacocca also will step 
aside 
