<TEXT>
the holding company seeing federated 
department stores inc and allied stores corp through chapter 11 
reorganizations wants to seek us bankruptcy court approval for a 
plan to retain executives 
carol sanger a spokeswoman for federated stores inc holding 
company for the us retailing operations of torontobased campeau 
corp said tuesday the proposal designed to keep executives from 
leaving to join rival retailers is still being developed 
it would apply to ranks from senior management all the way down 
to middlelevel executives in merchandising and similar jobs within 
the federated and allied store groups ms sanger said 
she said the proposal may not be ready to be submitted at the 
next hearing scheduled march 15 before judge j vincent aug jr 
who is overseeing the federated and allied bankruptcy cases and 
must approve expenditures but the proposal could be added to the 
agenda if it is completed 
theres still plenty of time to add things to the calendar 
ms sanger said 
she said the plan will consist of various performance and 
retention incentives and a reaffirmation of contracts and other 
benefits she declined to be specific about whether salary 
increases or improved benefits might be offered 
lewis rosenbloom a lawyer for federateds unsecured creditors 
including major merchandise suppliers and factoring companies that 
serve as middlemen between suppliers and stores said federated has 
not made any details of its proposal available to the creditors he 
said he did not know enough about the proposal to say whether the 
creditors would support it 
we are told that the plan will be disclosed march 1 at a 
meeting in new york itll be the first opportunity we have to look 
at it rosenbloom said i am aware of it we have no details 
whatsoever 
rosenbloom said the creditors recognize the need to provide 
incentives designed to retain key managers from leaving to join 
other firms during the chapter 11 reorganization but he said the 
creditors would want part of the managers compensation and 
benefits tied to emergence of federated and allied from chapter 11 
and to the ultimate dividend payable to unsecured creditors 
federated and allied both based in cincinnati filed their 
chapter 11 petitions jan 15 listing a total of 77 billion in 
debts the companies were saddled with the debt when campeau 
purchased them in 1986 and 1988 
the companies are developing reorganization plans while under 
bankruptcy court protection from creditors 
