silver futures fell to a 4month low on new yorks commodity 
exchange but other precious metals posted only slight declines 
after steep losses monday 
silvers weakness stemmed in part from the governments report 
of a recordlarge 105 percent drop last month in orders to us 
factories for durable goods indicating again that the economy is 
not as strong as i think the fed would like us to believe said 
anne orton a vice president of preciousmetals dealer deak 
international inc 
silver as an industrial metal would suffer a greater drop in 
demand than gold or platinum in an economic slowdown she said 
silver futures finished 7 cents to 73 cents lower with march at 
5075 a troy ounce the lowest settlement of a silver futures 
contract in new york since oct 9 
gold futures finished 80 cents to 110 lower on the comex with 
march at 408 a troy ounce 
platinum futures finished 130 to 180 lower on the new york 
merc with april at 50980 a troy ounce 
most frozen pork belly futures plunged the permitted 
2centsapound daily limit on the chicago mercantile exchange in a 
technically inspired selloff that erased nearly half of last 
weeks gains 
hog futures weakened on spillover selling from the belly pit 
while cattle futures ended mostly higher on expectations for firmer 
cash markets 
live cattle futures settled 10 cent lower to 40 cent higher 
with april at 7537 cents a pound feeder cattle were 12 cent 
lower to 25 cent higher with march at 80 cents a pound live hogs 
were 27 cent lower to 10 cent higher with april at 4982 cents a 
pound frozen pork bellies were 19 cents to 2 cents lower with 
march at 5127 cents a pound 
grain and soybean futures prices closed narrowly mixed on the 
chicago board of trade with the march wheat contract posting its 
first daily decline in a week 
wheat futures settled 2 cents lower to 1 cent higher with march 
down 2 cents at 394 a bushel corn was 1 cent to 1 cents lower 
with march at 245 a bushel oats were unchanged to 1 cent lower 
with march at 136 a bushel soybeans were 1 cents lower to 1 
cent higher with march at 561 a bushel 
</TEXT>
