<TEXT>
levi strauss associates inc reporting 
results for the first time since going private in 1985 said 
tuesday its profits rose nearly fivefold in its fourth quarter and 
more than doubled for its latest fiscal year as annual sales 
climbed to 36 billion 
the parent company of levi strauss amp co the worlds largest 
brandname clothing manufacturer disclosed its results as it began 
issuing stock to employees 
levi strauss said it earned 498 million in the fourth quarter 
on sales of 960 million for 1989 vs 103 million on sales of 
8219 million for 1988 
for the fiscal year ended last nov 26 the companys net income 
rose to 2723 million from 1119 million the year before 
the 1989 income exceeds the record earnings of 2237 million 
reported by the companys publicly held predecessor in 1980 
sales of 36 billion which increased for the third straight 
year rose 16 percent over 31 billion in 1988 
ninety percent of the companys stock is owned by about 100 
shareholders mostly from the haas family who took the company 
private 
the company is beginning a stock savings plan in which it will 
match 50 percent of employees savings levi strauss said it 
expects employees to own up to 10 percent of the stock within five 
years the company employs 31000 worldwide 
the company attributed its strong performance to higher margins 
on increased sales the sale of a minority interest in the 
companys japanese subsidiary and a lower effective tax rate the 
pretax gain on the sale of the japanese subsidiarys stock was 
718 million 
international sales increased 22 percent to 12 billion in 1989 
and accounted for onethird of levis business domestic sales 
increased 14 percent to 24 billion 
the years results were achieved during a time of significant 
changes in the retail industry said robert d haas chairman and 
chief executive officer they reflect our success in focusing on 
our core jeans jeansrelated products and casual wear 
a big reason for the booming sales was the success of the 
dockers line of casual clothes introduced in late 1986 and 
designed for aging baby boomers who have outgrown jeans the total 
dockers wear for men women and now children accounted for 
nearly 400 million in sales in 1989 more than triple the 118 
million of the year before 
the company also said it had repaid most of the 16 billion 
debt from its leveraged buyout five years ago it said it reduced 
its debt to 475 million 
we feel weve been one of the most successful leveraged 
buyouts said george b james senior vice president and chief 
financial officer who noted the company is seven years ahead of 
schedule on repayment of its buyout debt 
last year all our businesses were setting records it was one 
of those years when nothing dragged us down a satisfying vintage 
year he said it was a good year to start our public 
reporting 
</TEXT>
