<TEXT>
eastern airlines has asked the federal 
bankruptcy court to release 60 million from escrow to help finance 
its operations in march as the airlines continues attempting to 
reorganize as a smaller carrier 
eastern filed a request for the funds with us bankruptcy court 
in new york on monday company spokesman robin matell said tuesday 
from easterns headquarters in miami 
a hearing on the matter was scheduled for thursday the same day 
courtappointed bankruptcy examiner david i shapiro is due to 
report to the court on his monthslong investigation of eastern and 
its finances 
a committee representing easterns unsecured creditors mainly 
equipment suppliers such as aircraft and engine makers supported 
the airlines request 
attorneys for the air line pilots association and the striking 
machinists union opposed the request as they had easterns earlier 
petitions for cash the union lawyers have asked that every dollar 
withdrawn by eastern be matched by a contribution from its parent 
texas air corp 
eastern is asking that 60 million be taken out of escrow funds 
which contain around 550 million raised from separate sales of 
eastern assets since the airline filed for bankruptcy court 
protection last march 9 
a month ago us bankruptcy judge burton r lifland approved 
easterns request for 50 million to finance operations through the 
end of february that ruling was the fourth time lifland had 
approved an eastern request for funds bringing to 260 million the 
total withdrawn from escrow so far 
last week eastern reached agreement with the unsecured 
creditors on a new reorganization plan under which sister carrier 
continental airlines would make some payments to the creditors 
the unsecured creditors who are owed 980 million by eastern 
would receive about 490 million in cash and notes under the plan 
if the bankruptcy court approves the plan eastern says it could 
emerge from chapter 11 this summer 
eastern and continental are subsidiaries of houstonbased texas 
air the nations largest airline company easterns previous 
reorganization proposals did not involve the assistance of 
continental or texas air 
eastern still has not reached agreement with holders of its 
preferred shares who are owed about 1 billion the preferred 
holders objected to easterns earlier plan which would have paid 
them only 10 cents on the dollar and called for the liquidation or 
sale of the airline 
the airlines exclusive right to file a reorganization plan 
expired last tuesday 
the machinists union is continuing the strike it began against 
eastern last march 4 easterns pilots and flight attendants 
unions called off their sympathy walkouts last november but the 
airline had replaced the strikers mainly with nonunion workers as 
it rebuilt from the strike 
</TEXT>
